yield: per plate
components:
  - name: charred broccoli
    ingredients:
      - item: broccoli florets
        qty: 1
        unit: head
        basis: true
      - item: broccoli stem rounds
        qty: 1
        unit: head
        note: peeled, 0.5cm slices
      - item: water
        qty: 1
        unit: tbsp
      - item: salt
        optional: true
      - item: sesame oil
        optional: true
    steps:
      - cut florets walnut-sized; peel stem with veg peeler, slice into 0.5cm rounds
      - hot dry wok or pan, tiny oil — char in spots before adding any liquid
      - add 1 tbsp water, lid on for 60-90 sec to steam through
      - season with salt and small drizzle sesame oil
  - name: apple relish
    ingredients:
      - item: apple
        qty: 1
        unit: ea
        note: 5mm dice, skin on; Granny Smith ideal; Pink Lady / Braeburn also great
      - item: spring onion greens
        note: from 2-3 spring onions, whites and greens separated
      - item: rice vinegar
        note: generous splash
      - item: fresh ginger
        qty: 0.5
        unit: tsp
        note: grated
      - item: salt
        note: pinch
      - item: chili flakes
        note: pinch, or few drops sesame oil instead
        optional: true
    steps:
      - dice apple 5mm, skin on
      - combine apple and spring onion greens with rice vinegar, ginger, salt, and chili flakes
      - rest 10 mins — the acid lightly pickles and transforms it from diced to relish
  - name: spring onion whites
    ingredients:
      - item: spring onion whites
        note: from 2-3 spring onions
    steps:
      - thin diagonal slices
      - 'optional: soak in cold water 5 mins to crisp and tame the bite, then drain and pat dry'
  - name: plating
    steps:
      - place charred broccoli on the plate
      - spoon apple relish over and around the pork specifically — it's doing a job on the fat, not the potatoes
      - scatter spring onion whites over everything at the end
notes: |
  Designed as a supporting act: its job is to cut richness and provide freshness, not compete.

  Rich fatty pork + fried starchy potato = the plate needs brightness, acidity, raw crunch, and water content. Apple provides fruity sweetness and tart acidity that caramelised sugars can't replicate. Broccoli brings vegetal freshness and char. Spring onion brings sharp aromatic bite and color. Every element has a specific job on the plate, not just a third delicious thing.

  Centuries of fruit-with-pork pairings (apple sauce, Cumberland sauce, quince) exist for good reason: fruit acidity cuts rendered fat in a way that other acidities don't quite manage.

  The char-then-steam approach gives you two things: blackened, slightly smoky exterior (flavor depth, visual interest) and a still-crunchy interior. Same wok logic as stir-fried potatoes — harmonises across the plate. Don't skip the charring phase; broccoli steamed without it tastes like a different dish. The stem rounds are worth the effort — sweetest part of the plant and they cook beautifully to a near-translucent slide.

  Raw crunchy fruit or veg + sharp allium + acid + small aromatic + brief rest. Works anywhere you have a rich main: diced pear + red onion + sherry vinegar for duck; pickled cucumber + shallot for fatty fish; pomegranate + mint + lemon for lamb. Once you think in terms of what the plate is missing rather than what else sounds good, these suggest themselves naturally.

  Apple variety: Tart (Granny Smith) ideal foil for rich pork. Sweet (Gala, Fuji) lean hard on the vinegar. Pink Lady / Braeburn sweet-tart balance, best of both. Keep skin on — the colour contrast and slight texture against the fatty pork is part of what makes it land.
